  "instructions": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "Mix the sauce ahead by whisking together 2 teaspoons brown sugar, 1 tablespoon fish sauce, 1/4 cup soy sauce, 1 tablespoon oyster sauce, 2 tablespoons chili sauce, 1/2 cup chicken broth, 1/4 cup water, and 1 teaspoon cornstarch until the cornstarch is fully dissolved and no lumps remain. Set aside."
      },
      {
        "S": "Heat a wok or large skillet over medium-high heat. Add 2 tablespoons oil. Once hot but not smoking, add the shallots, garlic, ginger, and bell pepper. Stir-fry for 2-3 minutes until fragrant and slightly softened. Watch the garlic carefully as sliced garlic can burn quickly at high heat."
      },
      {
        "S": "Push veggies to the sides of the pan. Turn heat to high and add 1 pound ground chicken. Break into small pieces with a spatula and cook for 3-4 minutes until no longer pink and lightly browned. If using diced chicken breast, cook until internal temperature reaches 165\u00b0F."
      },
      {
        "S": "Give the sauce mixture a quick stir (cornstarch settles), then pour it into the pan. Stir everything together and cook for 2-3 minutes, stirring frequently, until the sauce thickens and coats the chicken."
      },
      {
        "S": "Remove the pan from heat. Add 2/3 cup fresh basil leaves and stir until just wilted, about 30 seconds. Serve immediately over hot cooked jasmine rice."
      }
    ]
  },
  "notes": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "For gluten-free: use tamari instead of soy sauce and gluten-free oyster sauce"
      },
      {
        "S": "Neutral oil (vegetable, peanut, or avocado oil) works better than olive oil for high-heat stir-frying"
      },
      {
        "S": "Thai basil with purple stems is traditional and holds up better to heat than Italian basil"
      },
      {
        "S": "Fish sauce provides authentic flavor - hoisin is sweeter and should only be used if fish sauce cannot be used"
      }
    ]
  },
